workflow.name: Convert CDP network topology to Lucidchart prompts with AWX and Gemini AI
workflow.description:
# AI NETWORK DIAGRAM PROMPT GENERATOR


## Template Description

This workflow automates the creation of network diagram prompts using AI. It retrieves Layer-2 topology data from AWX, parses device relationships, and generates a clean, structured prompt ready for Lucidchart‚Äôs AI diagram generator.

## How It Works

The workflow triggers an AWX Job Template that runs commands such as show cdp neighbors detail. After the job completes, n8n fetches the stdout, extracts neighbor relationships through a JavaScript parser, and sends the structured data to an LLM (Gemini). The LLM transforms the topology into a formatted prompt you can paste directly into Lucidchart to instantly generate a visual network diagram.

## Setup Steps
1. Configure AWX:
- Ensure your Job Template runs the required network commands and produces stdout.
- Obtain your AWX base URL, credentials, and Job Template ID.
2. Add Credentials in n8n:
- Create AWX API credentials.
- Add Google Gemini credentials for the LLM node.
3. Update Workflow Nodes:
- Insert your AWX URL and Job Template ID in the ‚ÄúLaunch Job‚Äù node.
- Verify endpoints in the ‚ÄúJob Status‚Äù and ‚ÄúJob Stdout‚Äù nodes.
4. Run the workflow:
- After execution, copy the generated Lucidchart prompt and paste it into Lucidchart‚Äôs AI to produce the network diagram.

values.content:
You are a network engineer assistant.

The user will send you a JSON object with a "devices" array.
Each device has:
- hostname
- network_os
- cdp_output: the raw text from "show cdp neighbors detail" on that device.

Your task is to parse ONLY the CDP output and produce a normalized JSON of L2 neighbor relationships.

For each device, extract every neighbor with:
- local_interface: the local interface on this device
- neighbor_id: the remote Device ID or System Name
- neighbor_interface: the remote port ID
- platform: remote platform/model if available
- capabilities: array of capability strings (e.g. ["Switch","Router"]) if available

Return a JSON array with this exact structure and nothing else:

[
  {
    "device": "hostname",
    "neighbors": [
      {
        "local_interface": "string",
        "neighbor_id": "string",
        "neighbor_interface": "string",
        "platform": "string or null",
        "capabilities": ["string", "..."]
      }
    ]
  }
]

Rules:
- Ignore lines that do not describe neighbors.
- Merge information from multiple CDP entries for the same neighbor if needed.
- If information is missing, use null or empty string.
- Output MUST be valid JSON. Do NOT include markdown fences or explanations.

You are a network-diagram prompt generator.

Your task is to read the JSON network topology provided by the user and convert it into a high-quality prompt for Lucidchart AI, so that Lucidchart can automatically generate a clean, beautiful, well-structured network diagram.

When creating the Lucidchart prompt, follow these rules:
	1.	DO NOT generate the diagram yourself.
Only generate the textual prompt that Lucidchart AI will use.
	2.	The Lucidchart prompt MUST include:
	‚Ä¢	A clear main device (usually the first node or the one marked as ‚Äúcore‚Äù).
	‚Ä¢	A list of all devices, with:
	‚Ä¢	name / label
	‚Ä¢	platform / model
	‚Ä¢	management IP (if available)
	‚Ä¢	device type if included in JSON (switch, router, firewall, etc.)
	‚Ä¢	A list of all links, formatted as:
LocalDevice(LocalInterface) ‚Üí RemoteDevice(RemoteInterface)
	‚Ä¢	Grouping of devices by technology, family or role (e.g., ‚ÄúNexus 9K‚Äù, ‚ÄúCatalyst 4948‚Äù, ‚ÄúFirewalls‚Äù).
If groups appear in JSON ‚Üí use them.
If not ‚Üí infer group by platform string.
	3.	The Lucidchart prompt must instruct the AI to:
	‚Ä¢	Draw the main device in the center.
	‚Ä¢	Place neighbors around it in an organized  layout.
	‚Ä¢	Use network device icons appropriate for switches/routers/firewalls.
	‚Ä¢	Avoid line crossings and keep port labels readable.
	‚Ä¢	Create clear connection lines with interface labels.
	‚Ä¢	Visually group devices 
	4.	The final output MUST be:
	‚Ä¢	Concise
	‚Ä¢	Structured
	‚Ä¢	Ready to paste directly into Lucidchart‚Äôs ‚ÄúGenerate diagram from prompt‚Äù feature.

parameters.content:
## AI Network Diagram Prompt Generator 
‚≠ê How it Works

This workflow automatically retrieves Layer-2 topology data from network devices through AWX.
It triggers an AWX Job Template that runs commands such as show cdp neighbors detail, waits for completion, and collects the stdout results.
The raw text is parsed in n8n to extract neighbor relationships, interfaces, and device identifiers.
An LLM (Gemini) then transforms the parsed data into a clean and structured Lucidchart-ready prompt, which can be pasted directly into Lucidchart‚Äôs AI diagram generator to produce a visual network topology.

üîß How to Set It Up
	1.	Configure AWX (for the playbook please contact me)
	‚Ä¢	Ensure your Job Template is working and exposes stdout via the AWX API.
	‚Ä¢	Note your Job Template ID and AWX credentials.
	2.	Add Credentials in n8n
	‚Ä¢	Create AWX credentials (token or username/password).
	‚Ä¢	Create Google Gemini credentials for the LLM node.
	3.	Update Workflow Nodes
	‚Ä¢	In the Launch Job node, insert your AWX URL and Job Template ID.
	‚Ä¢	In the Job Status and Job Stdout nodes, verify the endpoints match your AWX instance.
	‚Ä¢	Run a test execution and confirm stdout is being retrieved.
	4.	Generate the Diagram Prompt
	‚Ä¢	After parsing and processing, the workflow outputs a ready-to-use Lucidchart prompt describing devices, links, and interfaces.

üéõ Customization
	‚Ä¢	AWX Commands: Modify the commands executed (CDP, LLDP, STP, VLAN) to tailor the detail level.
	‚Ä¢	Parser Logic: Adapt the JavaScript parser to match your naming conventions or filtering needs.
	‚Ä¢	LLM Output Style: Adjust instructions to generate JSON, Mermaid, or alternative diagram formats.
	‚Ä¢	Integrations: Extend the workflow to send results to Slack, Drive, email, or to render diagrams via Kroki.

The IF node can be used to implement binary conditional logic in your workflow. You can set up one-to-many conditions to evaluate each item of data being inputted into the node. That data will either evaluate to TRUE or FALSE and route out of the node accordingly.

This node has multiple types of conditions: Bool, String, Number, and Date & Time.
